  "prompt": "Is there an Android application that I can use to lookup words anywhere on my phone, without needing to have the application opened?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several Android applications that offer a \"lookup anywhere\" or \"define anywhere\" feature, allowing you to select text in any application and get a definition without switching apps. Here are a few popular options:\n\n**1. Dictionary - Merriam-Webster:**\n\n*   **How it Works:**  This dictionary app has a \"Tap to Translate\" feature. You copy the word you want to look up, and a notification appears with the definition. You can tap the notification to see the full dictionary entry.\n*   **Pros:** Reputable dictionary, reliable, widely used.\n*   **Cons:**  Might require a bit more steps (copy then look for notification) compared to floating windows.\n\n**2. Oxford Dictionary of English:**\n\n*   **How it Works:** This app may also offer a similar \"Tap to Translate\" or \"Copy to Translate\" function, appearing as a popup or a notification after copying the text. Check its settings to enable this feature.\n*   **Pros:** Excellent dictionary source, rich content.\n*   **Cons:** Similar to Merriam-Webster, might rely on notifications.\n\n**3. ColorDict (Discontinued but Still Usable):**\n\n*   **How it Works:** Used to allow definition from any app by highlighting text and sharing it to ColorDict.  You would then select ColorDict from the share menu, and it would give you the dictionary result.\n*   **Pros:** Powerful due to its use of multiple dictionaries.  Supported many formats.\n*   **Cons:**  Discontinued, so updates and support are unlikely. Finding and installing it might require downloading an APK from a third-party source (be cautious of security risks).\n\n**How to Use (General Steps):**\n\n1.  **Install the App:** Download and install the chosen dictionary app from the Google Play Store (or from a trusted source if you're using a discontinued app like ColorDict, and understand the risks).\n2.  **Enable \"Lookup Anywhere\" or Similar Feature:** Open the app's settings and look for options like \"Tap to Translate,\" \"Copy to Translate,\" \"Define Anywhere,\" \"Floating Window,\" \"Quick Lookup,\" or something similar.  Enable the feature.  Some apps may require you to grant permissions (e.g., accessibility service).\n3.  **Select and Copy the Word:** In any app on your phone (e.g., web browser, email, ebook reader), long-press the word you want to define to select it. Then, tap the \"Copy\" option.\n4.  **View the Definition:**  The definition will typically appear in one of these ways:\n    *   **Notification:**  A notification from the dictionary app will appear, displaying the definition. Tap the notification to open the full dictionary entry.\n    *   **Floating Window/Bubble:**  A small, floating window or bubble will appear on the screen, displaying the definition.  You can usually tap the bubble to see the full dictionary entry.\n    *   **Context Menu:** Some apps might add an option to the context menu (the menu that appears after selecting text) to \"Define\" or \"Look Up\" the word in the dictionary app.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Accessibility Service:** Some \"lookup anywhere\" features rely on the Android accessibility service. Be aware that granting accessibility permissions gives the app access to information displayed on your screen. Only grant this permission to apps you trust.\n*   **Battery Life:** Features that constantly monitor your clipboard or run in the background may have a slight impact on battery life.\n*   **App Compatibility:**  Not all dictionary apps are fully compatible with all Android versions or all applications. You might need to experiment to find the one that works best for you.\n\nBefore granting any special permissions, be sure to read the app's privacy policy and understand how it uses your data.\n",
